<dl id="n42031b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n42" href="#n42031b">N42 (VI.B.31)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n42all.htm#n42031b"> 31(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> irrum / irruminated <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n42031b"><li>FW 167.07 </li><li><a href="../../flex/fd/lexfd.htm#n42031b">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/fd/l39fd.htm#n42031b">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n42031b">MS BL 47475-62v</ms> </li><li>JJA 47:255 <a name=""fad6" href="../../ff/fdra/fda.htm#"fad6">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/fd/fdd5.htm#n42031b">Draft: I.6&sect;4.5</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[Some of Liguori&apos;s questions to women:]</font> 1. &ldquo;Quaerat an sit semper mortale, si vir immitat pudenda in os uxoris? &ldquo;Verius affirmo quia, in hoc actu ob calorem oris, adest proximum periculum pollutionis, et videtur nova species luxuriae contra naturam, dicta irruminatio.&rdquo; <font color="green">[He tries to find out whether it is always damnable, if a man puts his private parts into the mouth of his wife? I truly affirm it because, in this act, due to the warmth of the mouth, the closest danger of pollution is present, and a new kind of excess against nature can be detected, called &ldquo;<b>irruminatio</b>&rdquo;.]</font> <small> Chiniquy, <a name="CPWC" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#CPWC"><cite title="source">The Priest The Woman and The Confessional</cite></a> (n.d.) 160</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
